In response to the some of the incredible ignorance, stupidity, and blatant trolling I've been witnessing on this topic, I want to try for clarity.  An agent that provokes the immune system to create specific antibodies to fight off a virus is pretty much the basic description of a vaccine.  A 95% effective vaccine (remarkably high) still means 1 in 20 can become infected.  But the supercharged antibodies your immune system produces in response to the vaccine appear to reduce the mortality of those breakthrough infections to almost zero (again, remarkably effective).  Viruses mutate to spread themselves quicker and more efficiently.  The more infections in the world, the more mutations produced.  Most all mutations die off or fade from the data because they do not offer the virus an advantage.  But Delta has the big advantage that it is so much more transmissible (and, BTW, perhaps more lethal).  It's breakthrough rate is also worse, ~30% of vaccinated patients will contract Delta Covid if exposed to it.  But luckily, the incidence of hospitalization and/or death for such vaccinated people who do contract Delta is only about 7%.  There is no zero risk scenario in all this.  That's not how biological systems work.  But the known risks of the vaccine are mostly minuscule and rare compared to the well known risks from Covid itself and especially its Delta variant.  Please consider getting vaccinated for your own sake as well as for your loved ones and society at large.  The world's scientists are not lying  to you, people - they are trying to preserve life.  God bless and help us learn to love each other.

That said, the vaccine trains your immune system to respond to and defeat Covid.  That means, if you get sufficient exposure to Covid, then it enters your body, begins settling in, begins replicating itself, gets detected by your immune system, and gets annihilated.  But, before it is eradicated, it may or may not produce a symptomatic infection, and may or may not reproduce enough in your body to infect other people.  Your symptoms, and any damage taken from Covid, will be small or nothing compared to people who weren't vaccinated (and the symptoms that you do experience may be more from your immune response than from damage done by the virus).  And your risk of spreading it to others will be a lot less compared to someone who didn't get the vaccine.

But the known risks of the vaccine are minuscule compared to the well known risks from Covid and especially its Delta variant. Please consider getting vaccinated for your own sake as well as for your loved ones and society at large.
